1	\chapter{Line bundles on schemes and the Picard group}
2	\label{chap:Picard_LineBundle}
3	
4	This chapter sets up the foundational Phase~B/C infrastructure: the type of \emph{line bundles} (invertible quasi-coherent sheaves) on a scheme $X$, the abelian-group structure under tensor product, and the pull-back functoriality. It is the smallest self-contained step toward the Picard scheme construction (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}) and feeds the Jacobian gap chain.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Pic_{C/k}$ in later phases.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Line bundle on a scheme]
12	  \label{def:Scheme_LineBundle}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle}
14	  Let $X$ be a scheme. A \emph{line bundle} on $X$ is an invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-module: a sheaf $L$ of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is quasi-coherent and locally free of rank $1$. Equivalently: an object of the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is invertible with respect to the tensor product $- \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} -$ in the symmetric monoidal category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
15	\end{definition}
16	
17	\paragraph{Status note (Phase C1, post-refactor).}
18	Following the Phase~C1 refactor (iter-109), the Lean body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} matches the geometric definition stated above. Concretely,
19	\[
20	  \mathrm{LineBundle}\,X \;:=\; \bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times},
21	\]
22	the units of the (commutative) monoid structure on the skeleton of the symmetric monoidal category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}). This mirrors the ring-side precedent $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,R = \mathrm{Shrink}\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,(\mathrm{SemimoduleCat}\,R)\bigr)^{\!\times}$ at \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.PicardGroup:407}; the commutative-group structure derives from $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:80}) followed by $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. No \texttt{Shrink} wrapper is needed: $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ already lives in $\mathrm{Type}\,(u+1)$, so $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ inhabits the same universe and the downstream \texttt{PicardFunctor}/\texttt{PicardFunctorAb} codomains have been bumped to match.
23	
24	\paragraph{Load-bearing transitive dependency on the monoidality of sheafification.}
25	The $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})$ instance underlying the commutative-group structure is supplied by $\mathrm{Localization.Monoidal.Braided}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Localization.Monoidal.Braided:118}), which requires $W(X).\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ for the sheafification class $W(X)$. This is the project's named-deferred sorry $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ (\texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Modules/Monoidal.lean:166}); see the load-bearing-disclosure paragraph in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}. Post-C1, every theorem about $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$, $\Pic(X)$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctor}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb}$, and the downstream Jacobian arc transitively consumes $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$; \texttt{lean\_verify} surfaces \texttt{sorryAx} in their axiom chains.
26	
27	\paragraph{Pull-back: hand-construction over a split named-deferred Mathlib gap.}
28	Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback} below was closed in iter-109 by a hand-construction that bundles the two iso-witnesses of a (missing) $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ instance into a $\mathrm{MonoidHom}$ on the skeleta directly, then lifts via $\mathrm{Units.map}$. The construction depends on the \emph{pair} of named-deferred Mathlib gaps recorded as Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} (tensor-preservation iso, the $\mu$-iso) and Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_oneIso} (unit-preservation iso, the $\varepsilon$-iso) below. The two are siblings of a single Mathlib gap — once Mathlib lands $(\mathrm{SheafOfModules.pullback}\,f).\mathrm{Monoidal}$ the pair collapses simultaneously to $\mathrm{MonoidalCategoryStruct.tensorObj}$-comparison and $\mathrm{Monoidal.}\varepsilon\mathrm{Iso}$. The named-deferral route is per analogist option~(c) of \texttt{analogies/c1-route.md}; see also the Phase~C1 row of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}.
29	
30	\begin{remark}
31	  Mathlib has the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the quasi-coherence typeclass. The combination ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' is not pre-packaged; it is the content of this definition.
32	\end{remark}
33	
34	\section{Group structure under tensor product}
35	
36	% NOTE: post-C1 — the Lean body of `instCommGroupLineBundle` is `inferInstanceAs (CommGroup (Skeleton X.Modules)ˣ)` (no direct `sorry`), but the `CommGroup` instance transitively consumes `instIsMonoidal_W` (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}); see the load-bearing-disclosure paragraph above.
37	\begin{theorem}\leanok
38	[Picard group of a scheme]
39	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup}
40	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.instCommGroupLineBundle}
41	  For every scheme $X$, the type of line bundles on $X$ (modulo isomorphism) carries a canonical commutative-group structure. The operation is tensor product over $\mathcal O_X$, the unit is the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_X$ itself, and the inverse of a line bundle $L$ is its $\mathcal O_X$-dual $L^\vee = \mathcal{H}om_{\mathcal O_X}(L, \mathcal O_X)$.
42	
43	  We denote this group by $\Pic(X)$ and call it the \emph{Picard group} of $X$.
44	\end{theorem}
45	
46	\begin{proof}
47	  \uses{def:Scheme_LineBundle, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
48	  \leanok
49	  Identifying $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ with $\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times}$ (the post-refactor body), the commutative-group structure is obtained by Lean's typeclass-resolution chain
50	  \[
51	    \mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})
52	    \;\Longrightarrow\;
53	    \mathrm{CommMonoid}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})
54	    \;\Longrightarrow\;
55	    \mathrm{CommGroup}\,\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times},
56	  \]
57	  via $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:80}) followed by $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. The mathematical content "tensor product of invertible quasi-coherent sheaves is invertible quasi-coherent, with $\mathcal O_X$ as unit and the $\mathcal O_X$-dual as inverse" is packaged into $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ together with the localised-monoidal infrastructure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}); commutativity and associativity descend from the symmetric-monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$.
58	\end{proof}
59	
60	\section{Pull-back functoriality}
61	
62	% NOTE: post-iter-109 — the Lean bodies of `Pic.pullback`, `Pic.pullback_id`, and `Pic.pullback_comp` are now CLOSED, gated only on the two named-deferred Mathlib gaps Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} (tensor-preservation iso) and Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_oneIso} (unit-preservation iso). The hand-construction is analogist option~(c) of \texttt{analogies/c1-route.md}, with the named-deferral split across a pair (was a single oracle at refactor-iter-109; the unit-half was split off during prover-iter-109 because protected signatures cannot return tuples). `\leanok` on the statement blocks reflects that the declarations type-check and that the proof bodies are closed modulo the two oracle isos.
63	\begin{theorem}\leanok
64	[Pull-back of line bundles]
65	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}
66	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Pic.pullback}
67	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes. The categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f \colon Y.\mathrm{Modules} \to X.\mathrm{Modules}$ induces a group homomorphism
68	  \[
69	    f^* \colon \Pic(Y) \;\to\; \Pic(X)
70	  \]
71	  by passing to invertible objects of the skeleton.
72	\end{theorem}
73	
74	\begin{proof}
75	  \uses{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup, thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj, thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_oneIso}
76	  \leanok
77	  The conceptual definition is $f^* = \mathrm{Units.map}(\mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f))$, i.e.\ the units functor applied to the monoid homomorphism on skeleta induced by a monoidal functor (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:111}). However, calling $\mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}$ would require a $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ instance, which Mathlib~\texttt{b80f227} does not register.
78	
79	  The Lean construction therefore proceeds by \emph{hand-bundling} the two iso-witnesses ($\mu$-iso = Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}; $\varepsilon$-iso = Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_oneIso}) into the underlying $\mathrm{MonoidHom}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,Y.\mathrm{Modules})\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})$ directly:
80	  \begin{itemize}
81	    \item the underlying function is $\mathrm{Functor.mapSkeleton}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ (Mathlib's lift of an arbitrary functor to skeleta);
82	    \item $\mathrm{map\_one'}$ is discharged by Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_oneIso} (followed by the projection $\mathrm{congr\_toSkeleton\_of\_iso}$ of an iso to an equality of skeleton classes);
83	    \item $\mathrm{map\_mul'}$ is discharged by Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} (followed by the same skeleton-of-iso projection).
84	  \end{itemize}
85	  The composite $\mathrm{Units.map}\,(\text{this MonoidHom})$ is then a group homomorphism $\Pic(Y) \to \Pic(X)$ as required. When a future Mathlib refresh lands $(\mathrm{SheafOfModules.pullback}\,f).\mathrm{Monoidal}$ the two oracle theorems collapse simultaneously into $\mathrm{MonoidalCategoryStruct.tensorObj}$-comparison and $\mathrm{Monoidal.}\varepsilon\mathrm{Iso}$, and the hand-construction may be replaced by the literal $\mathrm{Units.map} \circ \mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}$ form.
86	\end{proof}
87	
88	\paragraph{Functoriality.}
89	The contravariant functoriality $(\mathrm{id}_X)^* = \mathrm{id}_{\Pic(X)}$ and $(g \circ f)^* = f^* \circ g^*$ is recorded by the following two lemmas; their Lean bodies are closed in iter-109 using $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullbackId}$ and $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullbackComp}$ respectively, plus the skeleton-of-iso projection used in $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$.
90	
91	\begin{theorem}\leanok
92	[Pull-back along identity]
93	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback_id}
94	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Pic.pullback_id}
95	  For every scheme $X$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}\,(\mathrm{id}_X) = \mathrm{id}_{\Pic(X)}$.
96	\end{theorem}
97	
98	\begin{proof}
99	  \uses{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}
100	  \leanok
101	  $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,(\mathrm{id}_X)$ is naturally isomorphic to the identity functor on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ via $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullbackId}$ (existing Mathlib infrastructure); the induced monoid hom on skeleta then collapses to the identity via the skeleton-of-iso projection.
102	\end{proof}
103	
104	\begin{theorem}\leanok
105	[Pull-back along composition]
106	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback_comp}
107	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Pic.pullback_comp}
108	  For composable scheme morphisms $f \colon X \to Y$ and $g \colon Y \to Z$,
109	  $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}\,(g \circ f) = \mathrm{Pic.pullback}\,f \circ \mathrm{Pic.pullback}\,g$.
110	\end{theorem}
111	
112	\begin{proof}
113	  \uses{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}
114	  \leanok
115	  $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,(g \circ f)$ is naturally isomorphic to $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f \circ \mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,g$ via $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullbackComp}$; the same skeleton-of-iso projection transports this composition equality to the level of $\mathrm{MonoidHom}$s on skeleta.
116	\end{proof}
117	
118	\section{Monoidality of the categorical pull-back functor (split Mathlib gap)}
119	
120	The hand-construction of $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$ above depends on the \emph{pair} of iso-witnesses of an (absent) $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ instance: the tensor-preservation iso ($\mu$-iso) and the unit-preservation iso ($\varepsilon$-iso). Each is recorded below as a separate named-deferred Theorem. Together they comprise a single Mathlib gap; a future Mathlib refresh landing $(\mathrm{SheafOfModules.pullback}\,\_).\mathrm{Monoidal}$ collapses both simultaneously into the canonical $\mathrm{MonoidalCategoryStruct.tensorObj}$-comparison and $\mathrm{Monoidal.}\varepsilon\mathrm{Iso}$ structure fields.
121	
122	% NOTE: post-C1 named-deferred Mathlib gap. The Lean body is `sorry`; `\leanok` on the statement block reflects only well-formedness of the introduced declaration. Closure awaits either a Mathlib refresh landing `(SheafOfModules.pullback _).Monoidal` or a hand-construction of the tensor-preservation iso.
123	\begin{theorem}\leanok
124	[Pull-back of $\mathcal O$-modules preserves tensor product]
125	  \label{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}
126	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.SheafOfModules.pullback_tensorObj}
127	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj}
128	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes and $M, N \in Y.\mathrm{Modules}$. Then the categorical pull-back functor $f^* := \mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ preserves tensor products: there is a natural isomorphism
129	  \[
130	    f^*\bigl(M \otimes_{\mathcal O_Y} N\bigr) \;\cong\; f^* M \;\otimes_{\mathcal O_X}\; f^* N.
131	  \]
132	\end{theorem}
133	
134	\begin{proof}
135	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
136	  \leanok
